title: For Sale:  *******Scam Warning*********
postcontent:
Several Listing currently on the site that are clearly scams. If the price is to good to be true it most likely is. A seller asking for payment in money order sent to a location outside the state that the listing is currently listed in is a HUGE RED FLAG. If the seller gives every excuse in the book for not being able to do a Face to Face transaction it should indicate a HUGE RED FLAG. The seller asking that payment be sent to a P.O Box in some obscure area is another indicator of a scammer. Look at the listing itself does the listing seem rather technical with plenty of very specific details and the pictures seem very professionally set up. While not all will be scams it would be best to check GunBroker to ensure that info and pics didn't come from a GunBroker listing.

People don't allow your excitement and desire to find a great deal get in the way of your common sense. If you send money to these scammers you can basically consider your money lost Law Enforcement has little that they can do and the likelihood of you ever getting your money back is VERY LOW to non-existent.

Helpful tools for your toolbox: Do your research, if the deal seems to good to be true tread carefully. Ask the seller to jump on Skype or use face time on a smart phone. You as a potential buyer get to see the firearm to ensure that the seller is in fact in possession and you get to visually inspect the weapon prior to meeting up with the seller. Also and most important using Skype and or Face Time allows for both parties to get a visual on who they are dealing with and if you feel the need to take a screenshot to ensure that if for any reason any party intends nefarious intentions said party will not get away without Law Enforcement having a mugshot.

title: For Sale:  Savage Model 1917 in 380 ACP
postcontent:
I have a Savage Model 1917 pistol in .380 caliber.  The Model 1917 is the second generation of the Model 1907.  Most were chambered in .32 ACP, with only about 15,000 made in .380.  The condition is estimated at ~75% with some wear showing on the bluing.  By the serial number, it was made in the early 1920's.

It is a single action striker-fired pistol (the external hammer is actually just a cocking lever). This pistol functions and shoots well, and has very high quality machining. title: For Sale:  Anschutz .22 Sporter, Model 141
postcontent:
Offered for sale is an Anschutz .22 sporter, model 141.  This rifle was manufactured by Anschutz in Ulm, West Germany and imported by Savage.  It is chambered for the .22 Long Rifle.  It has a grooved receiver for easy scope mounting and the action is fed by a detachable 5-shot (or, 10-shot) magazine.  It has a 22” barrel, folding rear sight, hooded front sight, and the rifle is 40” long, overall.   

According to the proof stamp on the barrel, it was manufactured in 1965.  It is in very good condition for its age, with approximately 97% blue condition and light handling marks on the stock.  The blond walnut stock has a Monte Carlo cheek-piece, skip-line checkering, and a rosewood fore-end tip. There are no real “dings” in the stock, but there are a couple of small areas where the varnish/finish has thinned through to the wood.  The screw-heads are all in excellent condition.  Apart from the butt-plate, there is no plastic on the gun.  

The bore is shiny-bright and the rifling is crisp.  Mechanically, the rifle is excellent and it is a very accurate shooter.  The scope is a Simmons ".22 Mag" 3-9 x 32 with a plex reticle.  It is mounted with Burris steel rings.  Apart from the stock design, this model 141 is strikingly similar to Anschutz’ current model 1416, which has the same Anschutz 64 receiver and uses the same magazines.  The current model 1416 retails for around $1050.  I’m selling this rifle for $480, delivered.  Will send to your FFL or local gun shop.  

I have 30 additional photos I can send by e-mail.

 UPDATED REMINGTON MODEL 700™ TITANIUM GETS A NEW LOOK AND NAME - THE MODEL 700 ALASKAN TI
October 17, 2006

Madison, N.C. - In 2001, Remington revolutionized the world of production rifles when we introduced the Model 700 Titanium Ultimate Lightweight bolt-action rifle - the lightest production rifle on the market, rivaling custom rifles at a fraction of the cost. For 2007, the Model 700 Titanium gets an updated style, enhanced features and a new name - the Model 700 Alaskan Ti, available in nine versatile hunting calibers ranging from the medium range 7mm-08 Rem to the full-power .300 Win Mag. It is incredibly strong, impervious to the weather and amazingly accurate; and it weighs a mere 6 pounds!

At the core of the Model 700 Alaskan Ti is the strong, yet lightweight, receiver milled out of a solid block of Titanium. Spiral flutes are added on the bolt body and the bolt handle is skeletonized to remove additional weight while increasing bolt rigidity and cycling capabilities. And with all the great features of the legendary Model 700 bolt-action platform, this rifle offers the dependability and "out-of-the-box" accuracy that hunters and shooters have come to expect.

The addition of several new features to the Model 700 Alaskan Ti enhances performance, durability and updates its look. The new Remington X-MARK PRO™ trigger helps to deliver extraordinary accuracy with a trigger that breaks like glass, has virtually no creep and comes with up to 40% lower factory set pull weight. The clean 24-inch magnum contour barrel with Light Varmint style fluting is constructed of durable 416 stainless steel. The longer barrel length optimizes velocities while the fluting reduces weight and improves heat dissipation. The magnum contour barrel with fluting provides for magnum caliber chamberings (not previously available in the Model 700 Titanium) without adding significant weight. The barreled action is pillar bedded into a rugged Bell & Carlson carbon fiber synthetic stock, enhanced with a black and gray webbed paint scheme. This well-designed stock also features the new MaxxGuard™ protective coating which provides a soft touch, easy-grip finish for solid-handling in even the harshest weather conditions. Also new for 2007 is the addition of a hinged floorplate magazine with four-round magazine capacity in the short and long action calibers and three-round capacity in the magnum offerings. Completing this high tech package is the addition of sling swivel studs; receiver drilled and tapped for scope mounts; and revolutionary R3® Recoil Pad which significantly lessens recoil in this lightweight rifle.

Getting to the top of that mountain won't be as difficult with the amazingly lightweight and durable Model 700 Alaskan Ti. Getting your trophy won't be either.

The Model 700 Alaskan Ti rifle is available in 7mm-08 Rem, .25-06 Rem, .270 Win, .280 Rem, .30-06 Sprg, .270 WSM, .300 WSM, 7mm Rem Mag and .300 Win Mag at suggested retail prices ranging from $2105 to $2225. Visit our web site at www.remington.com for a complete listing of Model 700 specialty, high performance rifles.

October 17, 2006

Madison, N.C. - In 2001, Remington revolutionized the world of production rifles when we introduced the Model 700 Titanium Ultimate Lightweight bolt-action rifle - the lightest production rifle on the market, rivaling custom rifles at a fraction of the cost. The longer barrel length optimizes velocities while the fluting reduces weight and improves heat dissipation. The magnum contour barrel with fluting provides for magnum caliber chamberings (not previously available in the Model 700 Titanium) without adding significant weight. The barreled action is pillar bedded into a rugged Bell & Carlson carbon fiber synthetic stock, enhanced with a black and gray webbed paint scheme. This well-designed stock also features the new MaxxGuard™ protective coating which provides a soft touch, easy-grip finish for solid-handling in even the harshest weather conditions. Also new for 2007 is the addition of a hinged floorplate magazine with four-round magazine capacity in the short and long action calibers and three-round capacity in the magnum offerings. Completing this high tech package is the addition of sling swivel studs; receiver drilled and tapped for scope mounts; and revolutionary R3® Recoil Pad which significantly lessens recoil in this lightweight rifle.

Getting to the top of that mountain won't be as difficult with the amazingly lightweight and durable Model 700 Alaskan Ti. Getting your trophy won't be either.

The Model 700 Alaskan Ti rifle is available in 7mm-08 Rem, .25-06 Rem, .270 Win, .280 Rem, .30-06 Sprg, .270 WSM, .300 WSM, 7mm Rem Mag and .300 Win Mag at suggested retail prices ranging from $2105 to $2225. title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1885 low wall rifle
postcontent: The 1885 Single Shot was the first and perhaps one of the greatest of all the John Moses Browning designs. It was 100% conceived of and created by Browning in the frontier pioneer town of Ogden, Utah in 1878. Not only was it the first he produced, but it was the gun that started his relationship with the Winchester Repeating Arms company. They knew it was a superior single shot design and they knew it had to be a Winchester. The partnership began in 1885 and the Single Shot became the Model 1885 Winchester.

title: For Sale:  1941 Johnon semi auto rifle !!
postcontent: This rifle is a RARE 1941 Johnson military rifle, in 30-06 caliber it was shipped to the Netherlands purchasing commission by Johnson Rifles in early  Febraury 1942-- These were to be shipped to Dutch Military forces in Java , but the battles were over before the rifles were shipped. These rifles then bounced around and saw service worldwide by several armies and Special Units; however wherever this rifle served cannot be determined-- rifle is complete and has a great barrel, the barrel length is 19 1/2  inches and appears to have been slightly shortened. The front sight is original but the bayonet lug was removed, this was common on rifles shipped into Canada in the early 1950's, These rifles were also used in Chile in 7mm -Otherwise this rifle is in excellent condition and I however  replaced the operating spring with a new production  spring because the originals have deteriorated over the last 73 years  ! Rifle stock has one small repaid on the left side but that is about it !! All finishes are original !
